Click \s or type F4 to control case sensitivity in searching.
Click \s or type F5 to control the use of magic character sequences in searching. The available sequences are summarised on the lower portion of the dialogue box.
Click \s or type F6 to control the use of wildcarded expressions in searching.  Wildcards can be entered from the keyboard or via the icons in the lower portion of the dialogue box.
Matches any character
Matches the newline character
Matches any SINGLE alphanumeric character [a-zA-Z0-9] or underscore '_'
Matches any SINGLE digit [0-9]

X Matches the character ctrl-X
Used to escape special characters back to their normal meaning
Marks start of a set  eg. [abc] is the set of all lower case a's b's and c's
Marks end of a set eg. [abc] is the set of all lower case a's b's and c's
Not the next character (or set) in the find string
Zero or more occurrences of the next pattern element
One or more occurrences of the next pattern element
The longest sequence of the next pattern element
Used to mark a range of characters eg. a-z
Denotes the string which was last found matching the find string
?n denotes the n'th ambiguous subpattern in the found string
„xx matches the character whose ASCII code is given by the hex number xx
The string has been found, and is now the selection.

Click here or type S or RETURN or ESC to quit from the Find system.
Click here or type C to search again for the string, without replacing this one.
Click here or type R to replace the string, and search for the next one.
Click here or type L to replace the string, and quit from the Find system.
Click here or type E to replace this and all subsequent occurrences of the string.
Click here or type U to undo the last operation in the Find sequence. Click \s repeatedly to undo several operations.
Click here or type D to redo the last undone operation. Click \s repeatedly to redo several operations.
